## Class Distribution

The class distribution plot shows a **binary target** with moderate imbalance. The **Depression = 1** class represents about **58.55%** of the data, while **Depression = 0** represents about **41.45%**. The bar chart suggests approximate counts of **16.3k positive cases** and **11.5k negative cases**, although exact counts are not printed in the screenshots. This level of imbalance is not extreme, but it is large enough that model evaluation should not rely on accuracy alone. A **stratified train-test split** and metrics such as **precision, recall, and F1-score** will be more appropriate.

## Variable Summaries

The dataset contains a mix of categorical and numerical predictors. The categorical variables shown are **Gender, City, Profession, Sleep Duration, Dietary Habits, Degree, Have you ever had suicidal thoughts?, Financial Stress,** and **Family History of Mental Illness**. The numerical variables shown are **id, Age, Academic Pressure, Work Pressure, CGPA, Study Satisfaction, Job Satisfaction, Work/Study Hours,** and **Depression**. Categorical cardinality varies substantially: **City** has **52 unique values**, **Degree** has **28**, and **Profession** has **14**, while most of the remaining categorical features have only a few categories. The numerical histograms suggest that **Age** is concentrated mainly in the late-teen to early-thirties range, with a few older observations. **Academic Pressure** and **Financial Stress** appear to be ordinal scales, **CGPA** is concentrated roughly between 5 and 10, and **Financial Stress** required conversion to numeric because it initially appeared as an object column.

## Key Correlations & Feature Insights

The correlation output identifies **Academic Pressure** as the strongest numerical feature associated with the target, with a correlation of about **0.475**. Other noticeable numerical relationships include **Age** at about **-0.226**, **Work/Study Hours** at about **0.209**, and **Study Satisfaction** at about **-0.168**. **CGPA**, **Job Satisfaction**, and **Work Pressure** appear weak in comparison. The categorical plots add stronger practical insight. The clearest signal comes from **Have you ever had suicidal thoughts?**, where the depression rate rises from about **23.2%** for **No** to about **79.0%** for **Yes**. **Academic Pressure** also shows a strong monotonic pattern, with depression rates increasing from about **19.4% at level 1** to about **86.1% at level 5**. **Financial Stress** shows a similar trend, increasing from about **31.9% at level 1** to about **81.3% at level 5**. **Dietary Habits** also appears informative, with **Healthy** associated with lower depression rates and **Unhealthy** or **Others** associated with higher rates. In contrast, **Gender** appears to have little discriminatory power, and **Family History of Mental Illness** seems only weakly predictive in the screenshots shown.

## Missing Values & Outliers

No dedicated missing-value table is shown in the screenshots, so the missingness assessment remains preliminary. However, one issue is already visible: **Financial Stress** contains a `"?"` value, which likely represents a missing or malformed entry and explains why the column initially appears as **object** instead of numeric. This should be standardized to `NaN` before modelling. The **Age** histogram also suggests a few observations well above the typical student range, extending into the late thirties, fifties, and around sixty, which may represent genuine older students or possible outliers. The **id** column should be removed entirely because it is not a meaningful predictor. A sensible handling strategy would include replacing `"?"` with missing values, auditing null patterns across all columns, converting ordinal variables to consistent numeric types, and then deciding between imputation, exclusion, or category-specific handling depending on missingness rates. Outliers should be reviewed rather than automatically dropped.

## Ethical & Licensing Notes

The dataset includes **sensitive mental health information**, especially the target **Depression** and the feature **Have you ever had suicidal thoughts?**. This raises clear ethical concerns around privacy, stigma, and responsible use. The suicidal-thoughts variable is also very close conceptually to the target, so it may inflate predictive performance while reducing the model’s value as an earlier screening tool. The screenshots do not show licensing terms, so reuse permissions still need to be verified before publication or redistribution of the data. From a modelling perspective, the system should be framed as a **screening support tool**, not a diagnostic instrument, and conclusions should remain cautious because self-reported mental health data can be noisy and context-dependent.

## Next-Step Recommendations

The next step should be a structured preprocessing pass. The **id** column should be dropped, `"?"` entries should be converted to missing values, and **Financial Stress** should be cleaned into a proper ordinal numeric feature. High-cardinality variables such as **City**, **Degree**, and **Profession** may require careful encoding or category reduction to avoid unnecessary sparsity. Since several variables appear ordinal, those should be encoded in a way that preserves order where appropriate. Baseline modelling should begin with an interpretable approach such as **logistic regression**, followed by a stronger tabular model such as **random forest** or **gradient boosting**. It would also be useful to compare two feature sets: one including **suicidal thoughts** and one excluding it, to assess both ethical sensitivity and possible target leakage. Finally, model evaluation should prioritize **recall, precision, and F1-score** rather than accuracy alone.
